# Bootstrapping Methods for GRN inference

Daniel Morgan1 and Erik L.L. Sonnhammer1

1Department of Biochemistry and Biophysics, Stockholm University, Science for Life Laboratory, Box 1031, 17121 Solna, Sweden

### Abstract

Gene regulatory network (GRN) inference has been a cornerstone of systems biology for over two decades, illuminating the regulatory mechanisms that orchestrate gene expression. Recent advances in \-omics profiling, coupled with spatial data and multiplex technologies, have fueled the rise of multimodal networks, capturing intricate relationships across tissues, pathways, and biomolecules in increasingly complex, multi-partite frameworks. Yet, many traditional inference techniques remain rooted in simple statistical correlations, tying the expression of one marker to another under shared conditions. These methods often lean on assumptions of profiling efficiency and practicality, sometimes even forcing inference where data are sparse. Bootstrapping and cross-validation offer a way forward, sidestepping these limitations by iteratively assessing network stability, rebuilding structures with and without various factors to gain confidence, zeroing in on high-confidence regulatory links.

Keywords: Networks Inference, Stability, Bootstrap

### Introduction

Approaches for drawing consensus among available methods remain popular as newer techniques become available, with AI systems even being developed to suggest the best technique to use given data properties[1](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/5Nmd). This chapter introduces a comprehensive framework for GRN inference, covering various techniques utilizing bootstrapping: BINCO[2](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/Vxui), Random Lasso[2,3](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/Vxui+RIyy), TIGRESS and its implementation of stability selection, and the NestBoot algorithm, as well as a criteria for evaluating network stability[4](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/H8Pq). Bootstrapping serves as the backbone of these methods, enhancing the robustness of inference by repeatedly resampling data to assess the stability and reliability of predicted network links.

Available statistics-based methods are included in this non-exhaustive list: Least squares, ARACNe[5](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/R0zA), CLR[6](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/1z5x), c3net[7](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/n46S) (and bc3net[7,8](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/n46S+PdN4)) WGCNA, LASSO, Ridge regression, ElasticNet, Z-score, GENIE3[9](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/OW2c), PLSNET[9,10](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/OW2c+Jutw), PANDA (netzoo)[11](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/5hqQ), and TIGRESS[12](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/chhb). TIGRESS specifically combines Least Angle Regression (LARS) and *stability selection*[12,13](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/chhb+rN53) to create a powerful linear regression-based approach for identifying significant gene regulatory interactions. LARS offers an efficient feature selection method suitable for high-dimensional data, while stability selection increases reliability by evaluating feature importance across multiple bootstrapped datasets. In contrast, NestBoot builds on these concepts by implementing a nested bootstrapping[14](https://paperpile.com/c/4O2lrT/emaU) strategy that integrates multiple iterations of bootstrapping to control the inclusion of false links, and thus false discovery rates (FDR), providing accurate GRN predictions even under noisy data conditions. Nestboot can be implemented on top of any algorithm where variation is present *i.e.* between measured samples (time points, biological or technical replicates, etc) or in nondeterministic calculation e.g. LASSO; however for methods already invoking cross-validation it might add unnecessary compute time.

This chapter provides detailed explanations of each technique, including their theoretical foundations, practical implementations, and applications in GRN inference. The strengths, limitations, and parameter-tuning strategies for these methods are discussed, offering readers a comprehensive understanding of how to apply and optimize these tools for different biological datasets. Case studies demonstrate the practical use of these methods, emphasizing their utility and performance in real-world and simulated data scenarios. In this chapter you will practically learn to apply algorithms for inferring networks from biological data and importantly – for gaining confidence in those inferred links (Figure 1).

### Network Inference Stability

Measure is taken of genes under various conditions and fed into calculation as a *Y* matrix. GRN inference algorithms return an adjacency matrix *A,* whose inverse (*G, equation 1*) encodes the graph structure within this *Y.* This adjacency matrix can be signed — indicating activation or suppression of the target, or unsigned. The leftmost matrix in Figure 2 represents the expression levels of five genes *i* measured across various experimental conditions *j*. These conditions may include diverse cell types, environmental growth conditions, or targeted perturbations, such as knocking down the expression of individual genes. For instance, gene A's expression is measured under the knockdown of genes B, C, D, and E, and similarly for other genes.

Variability and noise inherent in the measurements and inference can be characterized under various combinations by sampling across conditions, so their effect can be calculated serially, highlighting signals otherwise quashed under certain combinations. Subsampling allows for robust inference of the underlying relationships, yielding an adjacency matrix of relationships for each subsampled dataset. Comparison aids in identifying commonalities and differences across the resulting networks, essential for evaluating the stability and reliability of GRN inference methods.

Similarity metrics can be employed to assess these networks using distance metrics such as cosine similarity, intersection or partial non-overlapping counts. Partial overlap or intersection offers a simple method for evaluating structural consistency. Let G1,G2,…,Gk represent the adjacency matrices of k GRNs inferred from subsampled datasets. Each Gt, f, for arbitrary *t* between 1 and k, is an N×N matrix, where N is the number of genes, and the entry Gt\[i,j\] represents the presence (or weight) of an edge between gene i and gene j in the n-th network.

We define the **consensus adjacency matrix** Gc​ with entries:

Where **I**(Gt\[i,j\]≠0)is an indicator function that equals 1 if there is an edge between i and j in the t-th network (i.e., Gt\[i,j\]≠0), and 0 otherwise. The sum of this counts the number of networks in which the edge (i,j) is present. T is the threshold for partial overlap, representing the minimum number of networks in which the edge must appear for it to be included in the consensus network. For each pair of genes (i,j) the formula checks how many networks among G1,G2,…,Gk contain the edge (i,j). If this count meets or exceeds the threshold T, the edge is included in the consensus matrix Gci​ otherwise, it is excluded.

### Tigress

Tigress formulates GRN inference as a sparse regression problem, utilizing LARS as a feature selection tool run repeatedly under the stability selection paradigm to identify transcription factor (TF) and target gene (TG) interactions. TIGRESS effectively infers gene regulatory networks by leveraging feature selection techniques and fine-tuning parameters (e.g., LARS steps and stability selection criteria) can significantly improve the model’s performance, making it adaptable for various settings. The combination of LARS with a robust stability selection mechanism is proven to be efficient for GRN inference.

Stability selection is a technique that enhances the robustness and reliability of feature selection methods like LARS. It helps to mitigate the instability often observed in feature selection when there are high correlations between features or when data is noisy. Stability Selection involves repeatedly applying a feature selection method (e.g., LARS or Lasso) on multiple, randomly perturbed versions of the dataset. These perturbations can be created by resampling (e.g., bootstrapping) or by randomly subsampling the features or samples. After each run, the method records which features are selected. The stability score for each feature is then calculated as the proportion of times it was selected across all runs. Features that are consistently selected (i.e., have high stability scores) are more likely to be genuinely relevant, while those that appear infrequently are less reliable. 

Figure 4 shows a benchmark of Tigress compared to lsco, Nestboot+lsco, lasso and Nestboot+lasso. It is understood that with significantly low signal, nestboot actually impairs native method performance.

### Bootstrap analysis via nested-bootstrapping framework

The previous section demonstrated that running serial calculations for comparison of results can shed insight into internal inconsistency in non-deterministic inference. In this way it provides a blueprint for arriving at stable consensus among networks inferred by the same method, just as comparing networks inferred by different methods would allow for overlap to be drawn from the intersection of shared links. One can apply a variation on this theme to control FDR of GRN links in a similar manner to how Tigress runs repeated runs of LARS under the stability selection paradigm. Arbitrary and user-defined bins of bootstrap runs can be grouped together for internal consistency. Figure 3 shows the detailed output of just such an analysis, where the Nested bootstraping of Lasso is run 1 million times and binned into 100 groups of 1000 runs. In this way we arrive at frequencies of link occurrence within and across bins, as well as overlap (intersection) of links between bins. Looking at overlap and frequency alone helps to find stability within the Lasso regression algorithm. Further comparison against networks that are inferred using similar bins of GRN links inferred on shuffled data allows the creation of a falsifiable hypothesis and against which to measure a false discovery rate. In this way you further constrain the included links returned, increasing the overall confidence in not only the method of GRN inference-induced technical noise but also RNA-seq processing, noise and error. 

### A SCENICPlus Case Study

In this section I will demonstrate the benefits of bootstrapping to gain confidence in link prediction using a commonly accepted and trusted method of GRN inference.  The code provided alters the snakemake setup of SCENIC+ tutorial to run many iterations, by which to arrive at stability estimates through (nested) bootstrapping. Simply run the functions in the pyNB package to install, run, analyze & gather summary statistics of link support across the NB runs.

SCENIC+ is a single-cell RNAseq method of gene regulatory network (GRN) inference, where transcription factor (TF) targets genes. SCENIC+ starts by constructing gene co-expression networks via weighted gene co-expression network analysis (WGCNA) approach or similar methods to cluster genes that exhibit similar expression patterns across the single cells. It then proceeds to identify potential transcription factor (TF) targets by analyzing motifs, where it leverages known DNA sequence motifs of transcription factors and performs enrichment analysis to find associations between the TFs and genes based on their promoters. It then constructs a GRN by linking the TFs with their target genes by combining co-expression information with motif-based analysis. Only TF-target gene pairs that have significant co-expression relationships and motif-based support are included in the network. There are further downstream processes conducted, but for our interests here, this provides a sufficient level of understanding.

**SCENIC+ Variability.** Figures 5-7 portray unique GRNs calculated by running the SCENIC+ algorithm 10 times on the exact same, generic *10x\_multiome\_brain* dataset.  Figures 5 shows high variability amongst 10 bootstrapped runs of the exact same *10x\_multiome\_brain* dataset data. Figure 6 shows leniency in forming the consensus amongst the 10 runs – strict 100% presence vs 80% – changing the network topology vastly. Figure 7 shows the overlap curve (see figure 3 for interpretation) for this scenic+ bootstrap run.

SCENIC+ was run 10 times on the 10x\_multiome\_brain dataset, a standard single-cell multiomics dataset combining scRNA-seq and scATAC-seq from brain tissue, using default parameters with varying random seeds to account for the non-deterministic nature of SCENIC+’s algorithms (GENIE3/GRNBoost2). Each run produced a GRN with 10–13 links per node, higher than the biologically plausible 3–5 links per node. Notably, high variability was observed in the links, particularly for “mega-hub” transcription factors (TFs), which exhibited several hundred different regulated downstream genes between runs. This variability, evident in the distribution extremes (Figure 5A: absolute intersection; Figure 5B: partial intersection in 8/10 networks), suggests potential artifacts due to the scale-free nature of SCENIC+’s algorithms, which may not always align with biological reality.

To address this, an overlap analysis was performed to derive a consensus GRN, retaining links present in at least 8 of the 10 runs. This consensus “hairball” GRN—a dense network with many interconnected nodes—highlighted KLF11 as a master regulator with high outdegree, as determined through nested bootstrapping-enhanced SCENIC+ inference (see Nested Bootstrapping section). The variability observed underscores the need for robust methods to ensure reliable GRN inference. Statistical measures, such as the Jaccard similarity (average 0.65 across GRN pairs), quantify this variability. KLF\_11’s role as a master regulator aligns with its known function in neural development, suggesting biological relevance despite variability challenges.

**Nested Bootstrapping.** Nested bootstrapping was applied to enhance SCENIC+ by running it 128 times on the 10x\_multiome\_brain dataset, using \`scanpy.pp.subsample(frac=0.15)\` to randomly select 15% of cells per run. Of these, 64 runs used true scRNA-seq input, and 64 used randomized input to assess robustness against noise. Nested bootstrapping involves two layers: an outer loop subsampling cells and an inner loop resampling within each subset to evaluate link stability.

Figure 6 illustrates link frequency (fraction of all links) per bootstrap support level on real data resulting in networks with a density of 1.7 \- 2.6 links/node and a number of genes ranging from 6507 to 8806, and shuffled data similarly resulting in networks with a density range of 1.7-2.5, ranging from 6579 to 8525 genes. Restricting the False Discovery Rate (FDR) to 80% effectively removed false links, as evidenced by dwindling support for randomized data and a spike in support for true data in the high-support region (\>70% of runs). This increased confidence in the inferred GRNs, with true data retaining 85% of high-confidence links compared to 20% for randomized data. These results demonstrate that nested bootstrapping enhances SCENIC+ by filtering out noise and stabilizing biologically relevant links.

### Discussion

Gene regulatory network inference is a vital tool in systems biology, shedding light on the complex regulatory mechanisms that control gene expression. As biological datasets grow increasingly intricate due to advances in \-omics technologies, the demand for dependable and robust inference methods has intensified. This chapter has highlighted how bootstrapping techniques, such as TIGRESS and NestBoot, significantly improve the stability and reliability of GRN inference, overcoming the shortcomings of traditional approaches that rely solely on correlations.

TIGRESS leverages Least Angle Regression combined with stability selection, resampling data multiple times to pinpoint high-confidence regulatory interactions based on their consistency. Likewise, NestBoot employs a nested bootstrapping approach to minimize false positives, producing stable and biologically relevant networks. These methods emphasize the critical role of stability assessment in GRN inference, particularly when dealing with noisy or incomplete datasets.

The SCENIC+ case study exemplifies the real-world advantages of these techniques. By running multiple iterations of the SCENIC+ algorithm with nested bootstrapping, we showed how variability in non-deterministic methods can be reduced, leading to more accurate identification of key regulatory hubs and fewer artifacts, such as overly dominant "mega-hubs." This practical application underscores the value of bootstrapping for single-cell RNA-seq data and offers a model for tackling other complex datasets.

Despite these strengths, limitations persist. Bootstrapping boosts confidence in inferred networks but cannot ensure biological accuracy without experimental validation. Moreover, its computational intensity can be a hurdle, especially for large-scale data, requiring a trade-off between robustness and feasibility. Future efforts should aim to enhance the scalability of these methods—perhaps through parallel computing or algorithmic refinements—to broaden their applicability.

Looking forward, integrating multi-omic data (e.g., transcriptomics, epigenomics, and proteomics) holds immense potential for GRN inference. Adapting bootstrapping to these richer datasets could reveal deeper regulatory insights. Additionally, emerging machine learning tools that suggest optimal inference methods based on dataset characteristics could simplify the process, though this area is still developing. Bootstrapping stands out as a key strategy for refining GRN inference, empowering researchers to confidently explore the complexities of modern biological data. By adopting these approaches, the field can progress beyond basic correlations, unraveling the sophisticated networks that shape cellular function and advancing our knowledge of gene regulation in health and disease.

**Figure 2\. Process of subsetting datasets, bootstrapping, and inferring networks.** An example subsampling into four datasets, each generating a GRN from relationships inherent to the underlying complete dataset. Links between genes are inferred in at least three of the four networks for most edges, whereas one link fails to meet this threshold. Using a simple partial overlap approach, the consensus network retains only those edges that appear in at least three networks. This method highlights the value of consensus-building in GRN inference, ensuring that the final network reflects the most stable and reproducible regulatory relationships inferred from the data.

![][image4]  
**Figure 3\.** Bootstrap support in NestBoot by average GRN overlap (transparent areas) and frequency of consensus links in bootstrap GRNs (lines). Illustration for user-defined FDR cutoff (here 5%) for link inclusion. The blue line depicts link frequency as a function of bootstrap support when using measured data, and the red line when using shuffled data. The link support at 5% FDR is shown as a dashed-yellow vertical line, which defines a bootstrap cutoff above which the measured data links are in the area to the right under the blue line and the shuffled data links are in the area to the right under the red line. In this illustration we set the FDR level for inferred links by finding the cutoff that makes the area under the red line 5% of the total area under the measured data. The overlap is the intersection of links in the bootstrap runs divided by their union. This indicates what level of overlap is expected by chance, and what level is observed in the measured data. Image from [https://dcolin.shinyapps.io/cancergrn/](https://dcolin.shinyapps.io/cancergrn/), LASSO GRN number 15\.
